04674nam a22006375i 9780520938809DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209388097 a10.1525/97805209388092doi  a(DE-B1597)648088  a(OCoLC)52996051  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aRA564.8b.O95 2003 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a305.262211 aOverall, Christine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAging, Death, and Human Longevity :bA Philosophical Inquiry /cChristine Overall; ed. by Christine Overall. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (276 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: “Death Twitches My Ear” -- t2. “Remember You Must Die”: Arguments against Prolonging Human Life -- t3. Age Rationing and “Generational Cleansing”: Evaluating the “Duty to Die” -- t4. “One Swallow Does Not Make a Summer”: Arguments in Favor of Prolonging Human Life -- t5. “From Here to Eternity”: Is It Good to Live Forever? -- t6. “The Death of Death”: Immortality, Identity, and Selfhood -- t7. Personal and Policy Implications: “Rage against the Dying of the Light”? -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the help of medicine and technology we are living longer than ever before. As human life spans have increased, the moral and political issues surrounding longevity have become more complex. Should we desire to live as long as possible? What are the social ramifications of longer lives? How does a longer life span change the way we think about the value of our lives and about death and dying? Christine Overall offers a clear and intelligent discussion of the philosophical and cultural issues surrounding this difficult and often emotionally charged issue. Her book is unique in its comprehensive presentation and evaluation of the arguments—both ancient and contemporary—for and against prolonging life. It also proposes a progressive social policy for responding to dramatic increases in life expectancy. Writing from a feminist perspective, Overall highlights the ways that our biases about race, class, and gender have affected our views of elderly people and longevity, and her policy recommendations represent an effort to overcome these biases. She also covers the arguments surrounding the question of the "duty to die" and includes a provocative discussion of immortality. After judiciously weighing the benefits and the risks of prolonging human life, Overall persuasively concludes that the length of life does matter and that its duration can make a difference to the quality and value of our lives. Her book will be an essential guide as we consider our social responsibilities, the meaning of human life, and the prospects of living longer.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAging. 0aDeathxPsychological aspects. 0aDo-not-resuscitate orders. 0aLife expectancy. 0aLife support systems (Critical care). 0aLongevity. 0aTerminal care. 4aEthics & Moral Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aOverall, Christine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024487040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093880940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938809423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938809/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  a